frustrations: 1) The SQL Server doc is unacceptably cursory, relative to the complexity of the software.For example, I've spent the past 2 days trying to use the COULMNS_UPDATED() function in a trigger, and have had to rely almost entirely on third-party sites. The examples are too simplistic to be useful (e.g. hardwiring column positions, rather than determining them dynamically).In another example, the CREATE TRIGGER page admonishes not to use "statements that carry out variable assignment". Is that just SELECT, or any statement (e.g. SET)? Variable assignments are, of course, integral to many triggers, and the language here is ambiguous. There's a passing mention of using SET NOCOUNT, but not enough information to make an informed decision.I work with many brands of database, and typically have to refresh my memory on the platform specifics every few months. Honestly, I hate having to switch back to T-SQL, because I know it's going to be so laborious to get back up-to-speed, given the paucity of details in the doc and, in turn, the need to scour the web for various thrid-party resources (thank goodness for StackExchange).2) I find the organization of topics for SQL Server in the left-hand navigation bar confusing, even after years of working with it. I keep thinking I'm going to get used to it one of these days, but I don't.For example, under the main T-SQL "book", why are there top-level sections for the various data type classes, then another "Data types" section that contains all of the same information?Why are there separate "Queries' and "Statements" sections - is a query not a statement?What do the topics in the "Language elements" section have in common - isn't everything in this book a language element?Maybe it's just me, but the organization of the SQL Server doc seems virtually arbitrary, compared to the equivalent doc for other platforms. I've resigned to using Google to search for the SQL Server doc pages I need, rather than try to find them through the nav bar (including its overly-broad search box).
like_best: 1) It's easy to find the page I want via Google search.2) The information in the doc is sufficient for doing basic tasks without a lot of reading.As is typical for Microsoft server products, the doc is geared toward doing easy things quickly. Unfortunately, doing more sophisticated things is harder than it needs to be, owing to the spartan documentation.

frustrations: I'm learning about SharePoint so I can implement it at our company. I was once worked in a company that developed intranets but that was 20 years ago before kids so I'm rusty with no programming experience. 1.Since it is an OOTB solution, I presume lots of small-med companies with tiny IT budgets will try to implement it on their own. I think you need to be more practical with case studies for smaller operations. Big companies will hire consultants. For example; Metadata is mind boggling since its loaded with jargon and no practical example.2. Also, you need a step by step how to list for developing an intranet. Step 1. Spring clean your filing system. Step 2. Find out what processes that are now manual can be automated. while you're at it, improve your work processes. step 3. Develop user cases. step4. Check band width (maybe that step 1). Step 5 Set up O 365 groups etc. etc. Write this stuff as if you've never done this before. I tried to get a consultant but they just wanted to take over, which I can understand as that how they make money. I think you need to keep this prescriptive and simple since you're trying to move this into an OOTB solution that companies can implement on their own.  3.Links are handy but it becomes a frustrating rabbit warren at times. 4.BTW, we have projects with standard libraries that go on forever. Why o why can't you save a site as a template? 5.Where does the accent colour appear - why is this not documented? I read somewhere that it was for buttons but that was not in sharepoint documentation - maybe another office product?why don't you have blue as an accent colour to orange - isn't it the complimentary colour on the colour wheel? 6.I can spend all day giving feedback but I'm trying to get me head around metadata. Is that user interface in admin friendly? There must be a simpler way but I haven't tried yet so maybe I need to be patient.7.
